    "recap_headline": "University of Pittsburgh Athletics",
    "recap_text": "STANFORD, CA \u2013\nThe Pitt Panthers (12-4, 0-1) lost their ACC opener at Stanford (7-10, 1-3) on Friday night, 9-7.\nA\nLorenzo Carrier\nthree-run home run in the ninth inning was not enough to mount a full comeback as Pitt fell in their first conference contest of the season.\nLorenzo Carrier\nrecorded his second two-homer game in the last week and has now hit a home run in seven-consecutive games. Carrier reached base safely in all five of his plate appearances on Friday, going 2-2 with two home runs, four RBI and three walks (two intentional) while scoring four of Pitt's seven runs.\nIn Pitt's last seven games, Carrier is 20-for-25 (.800) with 30 RBI, nine home runs and 18 runs scored. Through 16 games this season, Carrier is hitting .509 with a 1.200 slugging percentage, 10 home runs and 42 RBI.\nKai Wagner\nlogged his third multi-hit game of the season, going 3-5 with two RBI on his two-run home run in the seventh inning. Wagner has reached safely in every game this season.\nJoey Baran\nwent 2-4 with a walk, collecting his fourth multiple-hit game of the year.\nCaden Dulin\nhad a pair of hits as well, going 2-5 with a double and run scored.\nTrey Fenderson\nwent 1-4 and drove in Pitt's first run of ballgame on an RBI single.\nDavid Leslie\ngave the Panthers another strong start on the mound, striking out six and allowing just one walk over his 5.2 innings of work. The only blemish on Leslie's record on Friday was a three-run home in the fourth inning.\nThe Panther offense struck early with one run in the top of the first inning.\nTrey Fenderson\ndrove in\nLorenzo Carrier\non an RBI single to left to put the Panthers up 1-0.\nDavid Leslie\ntossed three shutout innings to start his outing and Pitt still led by one through three.\nStanford grabbed their first lead of the game with a three-run home run in the bottom of the fourth inning and led 3-1 over the first four frames.\nLorenzo Carrier\ngot a run back for the Panthers in the top of the fifth inning as he blasted his first home run of the game and ninth of the season. The home run marked Carrier's seven-consecutive game with a long ball.\nLeslie worked a scoreless fifth inning and got two outs in the sixth before being relieved by\nDaniel McAuliff\n. McAuliff came in with two runners on, and two out, in the sixth inning and got out of the jam.\nPitt regained their lead in the top of the seventh inning off the bat of\nKai Wagner\n. With two outs, Stanford intentionally walked\nLorenzo Carrier\nto get to\nKai Wagner\nwho made them pay with a two-run home run that put the Panthers up 4-3.\nThe Cardinal plated five runs on three hits in the bottom half of the inning to take an 8-4 lead. They added one more run in the bottom of the eighth inning and went to the last frame with a five-run advantage.\nTrailing by five, the Panthers would not go down quietly in the top of the ninth.\nAJ Nessler\nwalked and\nCaden Dulin\nsingled to lead off the inning, putting runners on first and second for one of the hottest hitters in the country in\nLorenzo Carrier\n. Carrier blasted a three-run shot, his second home run of the day, 423 feet to left center as he cut the Cardinal lead to just two.\nThe rally stopped there as Pitt went down in order following the Carrier homer and fell short in their ACC opener, dropping game one to Stanford, 9-7.\nThe Panthers look to even the series tomorrow afternoon as LHP\nVincent Spizzoucco\nwill make his fifth start of the year on the mound. First pitch is slated for 5:05 PM ET/2:05 PM PT."
  },
